        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cbc922e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>2:2.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Precursors of the Panel</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation is an outgrowth of the Coordinating
                        Committee for Multiple Litigation for the United States District Courts (“Coordinating
                        Committee”).
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        The Coordinating Committee was appointed by Chief Justice Earl Warren primarily to deal with the
                        flood of civil antitrust suits in the early 1960s brought as a result of the indictments of
                        various electrical equipment manufacturers and their executives for price fixing.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>District and circuit court judges appointed by the Chief Justice to coordinate activities
                        in the civil cases composed the Coordinating Committee.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Ultimately the criminal indictments were followed by 1,912 different federal court actions
                        pending in 36 different federal districts.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The proposal to create the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation came from the
                        Coordinating Committee.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Coordinating Committee viewed the procedures for transferring venue for convenience of
                        wit-<?page no="10"?>nesses under the existing venue statute[<footnote.reference
                                refid="I01c0d850680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>] and for consolidating
                        similar actions[<footnote.reference refid="I01c0ff61680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            2</footnote.reference>] inadequate.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01c0ff62680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>] The venue
                        statute required individual rulings by the judge presiding over each action.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Although there would probably be some consistency in the rulings, there would be no
                        certainty that all actions would be transferred nor that they would be transferred to the same
                        district.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Consolidation under the rules was inadequate because the courts did not have the authority
                        to consolidate actions pending in different districts.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Report of the Coordinating Committee reflects an early understanding of the purposes
                        of the proposed statute.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Report recognizes that<begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“court control of pretrial
                        proceedings and centralization of such proceedings, are basic to the proposal.”
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I01c12670680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            4</footnote.reference>] The Panel has implemented the centralization goal through its
                        transfer decisions; it has advanced the purpose of the exercise of court control over the
                        proceedings by deferring to, and encouraging the exercise of control by, the transferee court.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I01c2ad10680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">5</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel also implemented the experience gained in handling complex and multidistrict
                        cases in the 1960s by its membership and in its selection of transferee judges.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Many of the initial members of the Panel and transferee judges in actions initially
                        transferred by the Panel had been members of the Coordinating Committee or had presided over and
                        trials in the electrical equipment cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel thus was born with the “wisdom of the ages” in handling complex cases.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It has functioned well in many cases involving thousands of litigants.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It is now nearly as easy to imagine handling mass disaster or multiple securities cases in
                        the federal courts without the Panel as it is to imagine practicing law without the photocopy
                        machine.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
